               To us, the work is ritual: soil plucked, seedlings lifted, stalks clipped back, compost spread, petals opening like sudden revelation. 
               The garden is a ceremony, psychedelic and sublime, where labor and wonder are not separate acts but one gesture. In the words of Ken Kesey: “Plant a garden in which strange plants grow and mysteries bloom.”  
